ook offers a systematic study of the key spatial categories of the modern geographic imagination, including orientation, cultural landscape, and geohistory. In reconstructing the emergence of geographic science and the modern semantics of geographic space, this book approaches the literary and philosophical discourses of the eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries from a radically new perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aGeographyxHistoryzGermany. 0aGeographyxPhilosophyxHistoryzGermany. 0aGeographyxPhilosophyxHistory. 0aGeographyzGermanyxHistory. 0aGeographyzGermanyxPhilosophyxHistory. 0aRomanticismxHistory. 0aRomanticismzGermanyxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107042040 cprintz978080475839040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804787482?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804787482423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804787482/original  a978-3-11-070420-4  Stanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles